														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-3824200">
									

<p>You still haven't fixed the <a href="https://i.imgur.com/XTGcu91.png">misspelling in the logo</a> aaaaaaaaaaaaa-</p>
<p>Honestly, this feels way too much like SCP-3812&#160;2.0. It's a humanoid with a power to destroy other narratives that seems to have a sort of split personality disorder and in the last log threatens to destroy its own narrative (or atleast, a chunk of it).</p>
<p>Along with feeling a bit like a rehash, the clinical tone is half-broken<sup class="footnoteref"><a id="footnoteref-5059-1" href="javascript:;" class="footnoteref" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnote-5059-1')">1</a></sup> almost the entire article, &quot;destroying narrative = everything in that narrative vanishes&quot; doesn't quite seem to make sense, and the O5's are way too goddamn trustworthy of something that could just instantly wipe out their entire dimension if it so pleased, considering that their previous method of dealing with such anomalies was &quot;kill it before it even knows you're there.&quot;</p>
<p>But I enjoyed it. Despite all of that, I enjoyed reading it, so despite almost everything else pointing me to either nonvote or downvote, I'm not gonna do either.</p>
<p>+1 with a sour taste in my mouth</p>
<div class="footnotes-footer">
<div class="title">Footnotes</div>
<div class="footnote-footer" id="footnote-5059-1"><a href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.utils.scrollToReference('footnoteref-5059-1')">1</a>. The text is still clinical in tone, but the way the story is being told is essentially the same way as it would be told in a book, rather than how it would look as an actual report written after the fact.</div>
</div>

